Q0_CONSENT:
Please read through this information carefully before you continue with the survey.



DESCRIPTION: You are invited to participate in a research study that will ask you to answer questions about your emotions, write reflections on you life, view some images, and answer questions about the images you view.



TIME INVOLVEMENT: Your participation in this online survey will take approximately 12 minutes.



RISKS AND BENEFITS: The risks associated with this study are thought to be minimal. You may experience fatigue from the tasks and/or mild discomfort answering some questions, you can choose not to answer any question and you may stop participating at any time. We cannot and do not guarantee or promise that you will receive any benefits from this study. Your decision whether or not to participate in this study is completely voluntary.



PAYMENTS: You will receive $1.60 as payment for your participation in this study.



PARTICIPANT’S RIGHTS: If you have read this form and have decided to participate in this project, please understand your participation is voluntary and you have the right to withdraw your consent or discontinue participation at any time without penalty or loss of benefits to which you are otherwise entitled. The alternative is not to participate. You have the right to refuse to answer particular questions. The results of this research study may be presented at scientific or professional meetings or published in scientific journals. Your individual privacy will be maintained in all published and written data resulting from the study. In accordance with scientific norms, the data from this study may be used or shared with other researchers for future research (after removing personally identifying information) without additional consent from you.



CONTACT INFORMATION: If you have any questions, concerns or complaints about this research, its procedures, risks and benefits, contact the Protocol Director, Jane Stephenson at janestep@stanford.edu.



Independent Contact: If you are not satisfied with how this study is being conducted, or if you have any concerns, complaints, or general questions about the research or your rights as a participant, please contact the Stanford Institutional Review Board (IRB) to speak to someone independent of the research team at 650-723-2480 or toll free at 1-866-680-2906, or email at irbnonmed@stanford.edu. You can also write to the Stanford IRB, Stanford University, 1705 El Camino Real, Palo Alto, CA 94306.



Please save or print a copy of this page for your records. 



If you agree to participate in this research, please select “I agree to participate” at the bottom of this page and continue with the survey.

exp_Q1: I would curb my spending so that my savings would last until I was 120. I would move to a senior development that had a lot of activities to keep both my body and mind in good shape.
exp_Q2: Since I am assuming that I am in good health until age 120, I would travel abroad every year and visit the countries that I have not yet seen. I would spend months in certain countries since I would have the time. I would also do activities like play tennis, yoga if my body were healthy. I would not read as many books because I would move to a nicer climate to enjoy the outdoors and not be inside the house all winter.
exp_Q3: I would remain very active, still traveling and hopefully spending more time with siblings and my children, grandchildren and possibly great grandchildren. I would visit those seniors in nursing homes that are not in good health. I would continue to enjoy plays and concerts. I may limit my travel to within the United States and Canada.
exp_Q4: My goals would be to be extremely happy and grateful for living so long and in being in good health. Travel, spending time with loved ones and being in a state of continual peace knowing that I would be living that long!

exp_Q1: I would save more than I do now. I would cut down a lot of my spending, and save about 40 percent of my monthly earnings. This would help me to be financially independent even in my old age.
exp_Q2: I would not spend time on things that are not beneficial. I wouldn't cut down my working hours, to go for concerts or trips. I would rather work harder in my active years and start touring when I retire.
exp_Q3: After I reach 100, I would live in a quiet neighborhood. I wouldn't want to be disturbed by commuters during the day. I would want to live the rest of my life in peace and quiet. Also, I would allow my children and grandchildren to visit me on a regular for some family time.
exp_Q4: My goal would be to be able to save enough, so I don't become financially dependent on my family in my long retirement years. I would also want to make a more legal and proper plan for my life, mostly if I become inactive from year 100. I would also want to start a world tour the moment I retire.
